00:35:38,900 --> 00:35:40,999
Who does the dishes, mate?

505
00:35:41,000 --> 00:35:45,000
You.

506
00:35:47,600 --> 00:35:49,299
Smells good.

507
00:35:49,300 --> 00:35:51,199
What do you have
for us today, Burt?

508
00:35:51,200 --> 00:35:55,200
Its good Kiwi tucker.

509
00:35:55,600 --> 00:35:58,499
Don't let Burt see you
doing that.

510
00:35:58,500 --> 00:36:01,699
Here, don't spoil it
with all that sauce.

511
00:36:01,700 --> 00:36:05,700
- Sorry, Burt.
- Stone the crows!

512
00:36:08,900 --> 00:36:10,199
Are you going to watch
the movie, Burt?

513
00:36:10,200 --> 00:36:13,999
- Whats that?
- Are you going to watch the movie?

514
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:17,899
- Whats it called?
- Broken Barrier.

515
00:36:17,900 --> 00:36:21,599
- Its supposed to be good.
- Is Jane Russell in it?

516
00:36:21,600 --> 00:36:25,600
There's a spare seat
over here, Burt.

517
00:36:31,300 --> 00:36:32,599
Smoke?

518
00:36:32,600 --> 00:36:35,034
- No. Not for me, mate.
- You don't smoke Burt?

519
00:36:35,035 --> 00:36:37,699
No, I don't
and thats why people say to me...

520
00:36:37,700 --> 00:36:39,584
how do you keep going
at your age, Burt...

521
00:36:39,585 --> 00:36:41,399
and I say,
well because I don't smoke...

522
00:36:41,400 --> 00:36:44,799
so I'm telling you young monkeys,
don't smoke.

523
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:47,799
You can laugh,
but my Dad said...

524
00:36:47,800 --> 00:36:50,199
why contaminate your lungs
with tobacco smoke?

525
00:36:50,200 --> 00:36:53,334
The only thing you accomplish with
smoking is destroying your lungs...

526
00:36:53,335 --> 00:36:57,335
- and shortening your life.
- Kill the lights.

527
00:36:59,800 --> 00:37:02,099
Is Jane Russell in this?

528
00:37:02,100 --> 00:37:04,799
Go well, Burt.

529
00:37:04,800 --> 00:37:08,800
- Thanks, mate.
- Not for this.

530
00:37:13,600 --> 00:37:15,399
- Good luck to you, Burt.
- Thanks.

531
00:37:15,400 --> 00:37:17,999
Remember what I said.
Don't smoke.

532
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:19,299
I'm trying.

533
00:37:19,300 --> 00:37:22,299
Cheerio, mates. See ya.

534
00:37:22,300 --> 00:37:24,699
Welcome to the United States.
Customs to the left.

535
00:37:24,700 --> 00:37:26,799
Thank you, good to be here.

536
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:30,800
G'day.

537
00:37:34,300 --> 00:37:35,599
G'day.

538
00:37:35,600 --> 00:37:38,199
Please, stand behind the yellow line
until you are called, sir.

539
00:37:38,200 --> 00:37:39,299
Whats that?

540
00:37:39,300 --> 00:37:43,300
- Behind the yellow line.
- Yellow line?

541
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:53,099
G'day.

542
00:37:53,100 --> 00:37:56,899
Passport and customs declaration,
please sir.

543
00:37:56,900 --> 00:38:00,900
There you are.

544
00:38:03,600 --> 00:38:05,999
How long do you intend
to stay in the United States?

545
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:10,200
However long it takes me to get
to Bonneville and back.

546
00:38:10,400 --> 00:38:12,399
And the purpose of your visit?

547
00:38:12,400 --> 00:38:16,400
To set a land speed record
on my Indian.

548
00:38:16,900 --> 00:38:18,299
Indian?

549
00:38:18,300 --> 00:38:19,599
Mr. Munro...

550
00:38:19,600 --> 00:38:21,899
- So this is your first time to America?
- Yes, sir.

551
00:38:21,900 --> 00:38:24,899
You gave some rather odd answers
to the Officer...

552
00:38:24,900 --> 00:38:26,799
so we just have a few further
questions we'd like to ask you.

553
00:38:26,800 --> 00:38:30,800
- Well, fire away.
- Well, lets go over again what you said.

554
00:38:30,900 --> 00:38:33,899
Now what exactly do you intend to do
here in the United States?

555
00:38:33,900 --> 00:38:36,799
Well, set a land speed record.

556
00:38:36,800 --> 00:38:40,199
- And how do you intend to do that, sir?
- On my motorcycle.

557
00:38:40,200 --> 00:38:43,699
Its in the hold of the ship
at the moment and...

558
00:38:43,700 --> 00:38:48,400
they're going to unload it tomorrow.
Its an Indian, a 1920 Indian Scout...

559
00:38:49,300 --> 00:38:51,799
modified somewhat.

560
00:38:51,800 --> 00:38:53,299
You know what?

561
00:38:53,300 --> 00:38:55,799
- I think I've read about your bike.
- Yeah?

562
00:38:55,800 --> 00:38:59,099
Yeah, it was in Popular Mechanics,
a couple of years ago.

563
00:38:59,100 --> 00:39:00,899
Thats right, thats me.

564
00:39:00,900 --> 00:39:04,299
A Leslie Hobbs from Christchurch
sent that story.

565
00:39:04,300 --> 00:39:07,299
What was it?
Fastest motorcycle in Australia?

566
00:39:07,300 --> 00:39:11,300
Yeah, and in New Zealand.

567
00:39:11,500 --> 00:39:13,899
Well, I guess you're legitimate,
Mr. Munro.

568
00:39:13,900 --> 00:39:16,799
It sounds like we should be very
honored to have you here in America.

569
00:39:16,800 --> 00:39:19,499
- Well, thank you.
- We're going to give you six months...

570
00:39:19,500 --> 00:39:23,500
that should be time enough
to get the job done.

571
00:39:23,700 --> 00:39:26,199
- Welcome to the USA.
- Thank you very much.

572
00:39:26,200 --> 00:39:30,200
- Good luck, sir.
- Thank you.

573
00:39:35,200 --> 00:39:36,899
- Gears in the trunk.
- What?

574
00:39:36,900 --> 00:39:38,799
Bags in the back.

575
00:39:38,800 --> 00:39:40,299
Bag, back!

576
00:39:40,300 --> 00:39:43,799
Don't worry about me,
I'll do it myself.

577
00:39:43,800 --> 00:39:47,800
Strewth!

578
00:39:58,600 --> 00:40:00,699
Sit in the back, in the back!

579
00:40:00,700 --> 00:40:04,299
- What?
- You, in the back!

580
00:40:04,300 --> 00:40:08,300
Tell you something, mate,
you don't want to get old around here.

581
00:40:11,100 --> 00:40:14,899
Ta ra.

582
00:40:14,900 --> 00:40:16,799
- Where to?
- What?

583
00:40:16,800 --> 00:40:19,199
- Where to?
- Hollywood.

584
00:40:19,200 --> 00:40:22,999
Yeah, I want to go to Hollywood,
I want to see the film stars.

585
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:25,599
Okay, we go to Hollywood.

586
00:40:25,600 --> 00:40:27,899
Where in Hollywood?

587
00:40:27,900 --> 00:40:31,900
A motel on Sunset Boulevard...

588
00:40:32,100 --> 00:40:34,099
I hear thats a pretty great street.

589
00:40:34,100 --> 00:40:37,399
I don't know who you talking to lately.
Which motel?

590
00:40:37,400 --> 00:40:38,799
I don't know...

591
00:40:38,800 --> 00:40:40,199
a recommended one.

592
00:40:40,200 --> 00:40:42,899
Come on man, what do you think
I am, an encyclopedia?

593
00:40:42,900 --> 00:40:46,900
Drop me somewhere
and I'll sort it out myself.

594
00:40:54,800 --> 00:40:58,800
Must have a bit
electricity bill here.

595
00:41:01,300 --> 00:41:03,599
Firestone...

596
00:41:03,600 --> 00:41:06,599
Shell.

597
00:41:06,600 --> 00:41:10,600
Its all about cars, isn't it?
I've never seen so many cars.

598
00:41:10,800 --> 00:41:14,699
- You say something, man?
- I said I've never seen so many cars.

599
00:41:14,700 --> 00:41:18,700
Got to get around somehow.

600
00:41:21,900 --> 00:41:25,900
Look, there's a bowling alley.
Do you bowl?

601
00:41:31,200 --> 00:41:35,200
Whats he honking his horn about?

602
00:41:36,500 --> 00:41:39,999
Jesus!
Crikey, did you see that?

603
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:42,899
That blokes backing into that
geaser's car.

604
00:41:42,900 --> 00:41:45,299
He's crazy, he's nuts.

605
00:41:45,300 --> 00:41:48,199
He did it again.

606
00:41:48,200 --> 00:41:50,899
Don't stare, there's a lot of
crazy people in this town.

607
00:41:50,900 --> 00:41:54,900
I've never seen anything
like that before.

608
00:42:03,800 --> 00:42:06,599
- This should do...
- Whats the damage?

609
00:42:06,600 --> 00:42:08,399
US$28, plus bag...

610
00:42:08,400 --> 00:42:11,699
- US$29.
- What?

611
00:42:11,700 --> 00:42:14,599
Did you just say
what I thought you said?

612
00:42:14,600 --> 00:42:16,899
- Are you deaf?
- What?

613
00:42:16,900 --> 00:42:20,399
- Are you deaf?
- Yeah, I am a bit deaf, but I'm not stupid.

614
00:42:20,400 --> 00:42:23,499
- How much did you say it was?
- US$29.

615
00:42:23,500 --> 00:42:27,900
No, I don't want to buy the cab, mate.
I just want to pay the fare, thas all.

616
00:42:27,935 --> 00:42:29,799
- Where you from?
- What?

617
00:42:29,800 --> 00:42:33,099
- You a British?
- No, you must be joking...

618
00:42:33,100 --> 00:42:35,599
I'm no Pommie,
I'm from New Zealand.

619
00:42:35,600 --> 00:42:37,899
Well, this is America.

620
00:42:37,900 --> 00:42:41,199
And the fare, right there on the meter,
US$29.

621
00:42:41,200 --> 00:42:43,999
Open your wallet
and let the moths out.

622
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:45,999
I'm doing it, I'm doing it.

623
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:48,799
There you go, US$29.

624
00:42:48,800 --> 00:42:50,899
- No, don't forget the tip.
- What?

625
00:42:50,900 --> 00:42:53,499
Yes, we tip in America.

626
00:42:53,500 --> 00:42:54,399
Ten percent.

627
00:42:54,400 --> 00:42:58,099
- How much?
- Ten percent.

628
00:42:58,100 --> 00:43:02,100
Oh yeah, there you go, ten cents.

629
00:43:08,300 --> 00:43:09,999
Excuse me, sir.

630
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:12,299
- You look like a generous man, sir.
- What?

631
00:43:12,300 --> 00:43:14,299
- You look like a generous man.
- Oh do I?

632
00:43:14,300 --> 00:43:17,899
Yes you do. Would you like to buy
a flower to give to someone special?

633
00:43:17,900 --> 00:43:20,199
Well,
sorry I don't have any cash.

634
00:43:20,200 --> 00:43:22,599
Don't worry,
the money goes to a good cause.

635
00:43:22,600 --> 00:43:25,499
Its for an organization
that helps needy people.

636
00:43:25,500 --> 00:43:27,699
Oh alright, well, how much is it?

637
00:43:27,700 --> 00:43:31,700
- Just give what you can afford.
- Alright, well.

638
00:43:31,900 --> 00:43:33,999
They all look the same to me.
They're all green.

639
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:36,999
- Yes, thats why we call them green backs.
- That looks like a one.

640
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:38,499
- Look there's one.
- No, thats a ten.

641
00:43:38,500 --> 00:43:40,499
- Thanks, you have a good day.
- No, thats a ten.

642
00:43:40,500 --> 00:43:42,799
Hey come on miss, thats a ten.

643
00:43:42,800 --> 00:43:44,299
I didn't want to pay that much.

644
00:43:44,300 --> 00:43:48,300
Hey, come back.

645
00:43:50,600 --> 00:43:52,299
- Hey baby.
- What do you want?

646
00:43:52,300 --> 00:43:54,799
- You wanna go?
- Go where?

647
00:43:54,800 --> 00:43:57,999
- Go inside.
- I'm going inside.

648
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:00,099
I'll take you around the world.

649
00:44:00,100 --> 00:44:01,999
I've just come from halfway
around the world.

650
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:03,734
15 bucks, baby.

651
00:44:03,735 --> 00:44:05,199
15 bucks.

652
00:44:05,200 --> 00:44:09,200
No, sorry, go away.

653
00:44:14,200 --> 00:44:18,200
Hello.

654
00:44:20,300 --> 00:44:23,534
- I need a room.
- A room will cost you five bucks an hour.

655
00:44:23,535 --> 00:44:25,699
I'm planning on staying
a wee bit longer than that.

656
00:44:25,700 --> 00:44:28,499
- How long?
- I don't know, a couple of days I guess.

657
00:44:28,500 --> 00:44:30,899
- Double occupancy?
- What?

658
00:44:30,900 --> 00:44:32,499
Double occupancy?

659
00:44:32,500 --> 00:44:35,699
No, just me, myself and I.

660
00:44:35,700 --> 00:44:39,700
Will it cost a lot because
I can't afford a lot.

661
00:44:40,200 --> 00:44:42,499
- You a member of Triple A?
- What?

662
00:44:42,500 --> 00:44:45,199
- Are you a Triple A member?
- Never heard of them.

663
00:44:45,200 --> 00:44:46,599
Never heard of Triple A?

664
00:44:46,600 --> 00:44:50,600
No Miss Brittle Britches,
I have not heard of Triple A.

665
00:44:51,400 --> 00:44:53,434
Okay, lets just say
you are a member doll.

666
00:44:53,435 --> 00:44:56,699
- Alright.
- Thatll save you ten percent.

667
00:44:56,700 --> 00:44:59,099
How does 22 bucks a night sound?

668
00:44:59,100 --> 00:45:02,299
That much? Is that cheap?

669
00:45:02,300 --> 00:45:06,300
Honey, thats cheaper than cheap.

670
00:45:07,000 --> 00:45:10,099
- Whats your name?
- Tina Washington.

671
00:45:10,100 --> 00:45:11,399
Well, Tina Washington,

672
00:45:11,400 --> 00:45:14,299
I want you to have this,
it might cheer you up a bit.

673
00:45:14,300 --> 00:45:16,899
Get some of that muck
off your pluck.

674
00:45:16,900 --> 00:45:18,799
Well, thank you.

675
00:45:18,800 --> 00:45:21,134
Thats the first nice thing
thats happened round here all week.

676
00:45:21,135 --> 00:45:22,799
You're welcome.

677
00:45:22,800 --> 00:45:25,899
My name's Burt Munro.
From New Zealand.

678
00:45:25,900 --> 00:45:27,599
I'm from down under.

679
00:45:27,600 --> 00:45:29,999
Well, hello, Burt Munro
from New Zealand down under.

680
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:32,799
I tell you,
I've had a heck of a night.

681
00:45:32,800 --> 00:45:36,800
Welcome to Hollyweird.

682
00:46:26,300 --> 00:46:27,999
Hello?

683
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:31,299
Anybody home?

684
00:46:31,300 --> 00:46:33,599
- Hello, Tina.
- Good morning, Burt.

685
00:46:33,600 --> 00:46:36,399
You still here?

686
00:46:36,400 --> 00:46:39,499
Thats why you were
so crabby last night.

687
00:46:39,500 --> 00:46:41,099
Don't you ever get any sleep?

688
00:46:41,100 --> 00:46:42,799
I work a night shift.

689
00:46:42,800 --> 00:46:46,499
I'm out of here as soon as James
turns up and he's late.

690
00:46:46,500 --> 00:46:49,999
Yeah, could you phone
this number for me?

691
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:53,699
Yeah, its a shipping company
and they've got a big box of mine...

692
00:46:53,700 --> 00:46:57,700
and I want to know how
to arrange to get it.

693
00:46:59,200 --> 00:47:01,499
No, you talk to them,
they'll never get my accent.

694
00:47:01,500 --> 00:47:04,099
Okay, what do you want me
to ask them? One moment please.

695
00:47:04,100 --> 00:47:08,800
Ask them when a Burt Munro's box
containing the motorcycle...

696
00:47:08,835 --> 00:47:10,799
will be ready for pick up.

697
00:47:10,800 --> 00:47:13,399
Hello, I'm calling
for Mr. Burt Munro.

698
00:47:13,400 --> 00:47:16,234
Yes, he'd like to know when the box
containing his motorcycle...

699
00:47:16,235 --> 00:47:18,899
- will be available for pick up.
- What ship?

700
00:47:18,900 --> 00:47:21,499
- What ship?
- Rangatira from New Zealand.

701
00:47:21,500 --> 00:47:23,799
The Rangatira from New Zealand.

702
00:47:23,800 --> 00:47:27,499
- Its arrived.
- So he can claim it?

703
00:47:27,500 --> 00:47:30,199
Tomorrow from the Long Beach
customs holding area.

704
00:47:30,200 --> 00:47:32,399
Okay, thank you, I'll tell him.
Bye-bye.

705
00:47:32,400 --> 00:47:34,299
That was pretty fast.

706
00:47:34,300 --> 00:47:37,999
You're late.

707
00:47:38,000 --> 00:47:42,000
I can't stand another minute in
this place. Let me buy you breakfast.

708
00:47:44,800 --> 00:47:46,499
Well, this is great.

709
00:47:46,500 --> 00:47:50,500
You know, I've never seen
a menu with photographs before.

710
00:47:51,500 --> 00:47:53,299
- Are you ready to order, sir?
- What?

711
00:47:53,300 --> 00:47:56,299
- Are you ready?
- Oh yes...

712
00:47:56,300 --> 00:48:00,300
I think the Double Delight,
thats for me.

713
00:48:00,700 --> 00:48:02,699
- How would you like your eggs?
- What?

714
00:48:02,700 --> 00:48:05,099
How would you like your eggs?

715
00:48:05,100 --> 00:48:07,199
Well, I'd like them cooked.

716
00:48:07,200 --> 00:48:10,499
Sunny side up? Over easy?

717
00:48:10,500 --> 00:48:14,500
- I don't know, whatever you recommend.
- Over easy's best.

718
00:48:14,600 --> 00:48:16,399
Alright, eggs over easy.

719
00:48:16,400 --> 00:48:17,899
Make that two.

720
00:48:17,900 --> 00:48:20,799
Over easy.
I must remember that.

721
00:48:20,800 --> 00:48:24,299
Yeah, I like this American
breakfast thing.

722
00:48:24,300 --> 00:48:26,999
Its good.

723
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:31,400
So my girl, where's the best place
for me to get a used car?

724
00:48:31,600 --> 00:48:33,399
The Valley.

725
00:48:33,400 --> 00:48:35,499
After breakfast I could
take you there.

726
00:48:35,500 --> 00:48:38,499
Oh Well, thank you.

727
00:48:38,500 --> 00:48:42,299
And I'm not a girl.

728
00:48:42,300 --> 00:48:46,300
I'm a boy.

729
00:48:48,400 --> 00:48:50,834
I thought there was something
a little odd about you.

730
00:48:50,835 --> 00:48:54,835
But hey,
you're still a sweetheart.

731
00:48:56,600 --> 00:49:00,600
Yep.

732
00:49:11,700 --> 00:49:13,199
Thanks a million, Tina.

733
00:49:13,200 --> 00:49:15,999
Hey,
there are stacks of cars here.

734
00:49:16,000 --> 00:49:19,499
- I'll be back in the motel later on.
- Bye.

735
00:49:19,500 --> 00:49:23,500
Bye.

736
00:49:26,800 --> 00:49:28,499
How may I help you, sir?

737
00:49:28,500 --> 00:49:32,434
Yeah, I want to buy a car,
a cheap car, a very cheap car.

738
00:49:32,435 --> 00:49:34,999
Well, you've come
to the right place, amigo.

739
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:39,300
In fact, if you can find cars like this
any cheaper, they're probably stolen.

740
00:49:39,500 --> 00:49:43,199
My name's Burt, Burt Munro
from New Zealand. Nice to meet you.

741
00:49:43,200 --> 00:49:45,799
I'm Fernando from El Salvador,
nice to meet you, Mr. Munro.

742
00:49:45,800 --> 00:49:48,999
- You can call me Burt.
- Alright, Mr. Burt.

743
00:49:49,000 --> 00:49:52,234
So how much were you looking
to spend here Mr. Burt?

